[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] A signal is an asynchronous notification sent to a process or to a specific thread within the same process to notify it of an event.
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] Common uses of signals are to interrupt, suspend, terminate or kill a process.
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] Signals originated in 1970s Bell Labs Unix and were later specified in the POSIX standard.
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] When a signal is sent, the operating system interrupts the target process's normal flow of execution to deliver the signal.
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] Execution can be interrupted during any non-atomic instruction.
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] If the process has previously registered a **signal handler**, that routine is executed.
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] Otherwise, the default signal handler is executed.
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] Embedded programs may find signals useful for inter-process communications, as signals are notable for their algorithmic efficiency.
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] Signals are similar to interrupts, the difference being that interrupts are mediated by the CPU and handled by the kernel while signals are mediated by the kernel (possibly via system calls) and handled by individual processes.
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] The kernel may pass an interrupt as a signal to the process that caused it (typical examples are SIGSEGV, SIGBUS, SIGILL and SIGFPE).
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] The kill(2) system call sends a specified signal to a specified process, if permissions allow.
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] Similarly, the kill(1) command allows a user to send signals to processes.
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] The raise(3) library function sends the specified signal to the current process.
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] Exceptions such as division by zero, segmentation violation (SIGSEGV), and floating point exception (SIGFPE) will cause a core dump and terminate the program.
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] The kernel can generate signals to notify processes of events.
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] For example, SIGPIPE will be generated when a process writes to a pipe which has been closed by the reader; by default, this causes the process to terminate, which is convenient when constructing shell pipelines.
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] These default key combinations with modern operating systems can be changed with the stty command.
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] Signal handlers can be installed with the signal(2) or sigaction(2) system call.
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] If a signal handler is not installed for a particular signal, the default handler is used.
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] Otherwise the signal is intercepted and the signal handler is invoked.
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] The process can also specify two default behaviors, without creating a handler: ignore the signal (SIG_IGN) and use the default signal handler (SIG_DFL).
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] There are two signals which cannot be intercepted and handled: SIGKILL and SIGSTOP.
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] Signal handling is vulnerable to race conditions.
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] As signals are asynchronous, another signal (even of the same type) can be delivered to the process during execution of the signal handling routine.
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] The sigprocmask(2) call can be used to block and unblock delivery of signals.
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] Blocked signals are not delivered to the process until unblocked.
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] Signals that cannot be ignored (SIGKILL and SIGSTOP) cannot be blocked.
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] Signals can cause the interruption of a system call in progress, leaving it to the application to manage a non-transparent restart.
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] Signal handlers should be written in a way that does not result in any unwanted side-effects, e.g. errno alteration, signal mask alteration, signal disposition change, and other global process attribute changes.
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] Use of non-reentrant functions, e.g., malloc or printf, inside signal handlers is also unsafe.
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] In particular, the POSIX specification and the Linux man page signal (7) require that all system functions directly or *indirectly* called from a signal function are *async-signal safe*.
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] The signal-safety(7) man page gives a list of such async-signal safe system functions (practically the system calls).
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] It is suggested to simply set some `volatile sig_atomic_t` variable in a signal handler, and to test it elsewhere.
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] Signal handlers can instead put the signal into a queue and immediately return.
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] The main thread will then continue "uninterrupted" until signals are taken from the queue, such as in an event loop.
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] "Uninterrupted" here means that operations that block may return prematurely and must be resumed, as mentioned above.
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] Signals should be processed from the queue on the main thread and not by worker pools, as that reintroduces the problem of asynchronicity.
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] However, managing a queue is not possible in an async-signal safe way with only `sig_atomic_t`, as only single reads and writes to such variables are guaranteed to be atomic, not increments or (fetch-and)-decrements, as would be required for a queue.
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] Thus, effectively, only one signal per handler can be queued safely with `sig_atomic_t` until it has been processed.
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] A process's execution may result in the generation of a hardware exception, for instance, if the process attempts to divide by zero or incurs a page fault.
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] In Unix-like operating systems, this event automatically changes the processor context to start executing a kernel exception handler.
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] In case of some exceptions, such as a page fault, the kernel has sufficient information to fully handle the event itself and resume the process's execution.
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] For other exceptions, however, the kernel cannot process them intelligently and it must defer the exception handling operation to the faulting process.
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] This deferral is achieved via the signal mechanism, wherein the kernel sends to the process a signal corresponding to the current exception.
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] For example, if a process attempted integer divide by zero on an x86 CPU, a *divide error* exception would be generated and cause the kernel to send the SIGFPE signal to the process.
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] Similarly, if the process attempted to access a memory address outside of its virtual address space, the kernel would notify the process of this violation via a SIGSEGV (segmentation violation signal).
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] The exact mapping between signal names and exceptions is obviously dependent upon the CPU, since exception types differ between architectures.
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] The list below documents the signals specified in the Single Unix Specification Version 5.
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] All signals are defined as macro constants in the `<signal.h>` header file.
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] The name of the macro constant consists of a "SIG" prefix followed by a mnemonic name for the signal.
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] A process can define how to handle incoming POSIX signals.
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] If a process does not define a behaviour for a signal, then the *default handler* for that signal is being used.
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] The table below lists some default actions for POSIX-compliant UNIX systems, such as FreeBSD, OpenBSD and Linux.
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] For most signals the corresponding signal number is implementation-defined.
[src:unix-signals/signal-ipc] This column lists the numbers specified in the POSIX standard.
